dismissalText.commentary: Ahmed Shehzad b Henry 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 2m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: what a delivery! Off stump cartwheels as Henry opens Shehzad up! Speared the ball in at a very full length and it curls away late. Shehzad can't quite be blamed for being stuck on the crease against a ball like that. Pushes with his hands and next second, he hears timber!

dismissalText.commentary: Nasir Jamshed lbw b Anderson 30 (46b 2x4 1x6 53m) SR: 65.21

dismissalComment.html: his footwork has been suspect all through the innings. He was relying solely on his balance and timing so far but this time he's misread an offcutter and has found himself plumb in front. Anderson knew straight away, had a giant grin all through the appeal as the ball gripped in the pitch and veered in at Jamshed to beat the inside edge and hit the back pad in front of all three stumps

dismissalText.commentary: Umar Akmal run out (McClenaghan) 29 (37b 1x4 0x6 65m) SR: 78.37

dismissalComment.html: that is so unfortunate! Younis has caned a straight drive and Mitch Mc manages to get enough of a deflection back onto the stumps, one of which cartwheels on impact, with Akmal backing up! Among the worst dismissals in cricket

dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan b Vettori 103 (117b 4x4 2x6 199m) SR: 88.03

dismissalComment.html: flat, full and straight. Vettori has toppled Younis and has coolly gone back to the umpire to collect his cap. Wild slog from Younis and he realised his mistake the moment he swung past the ball

dismissalText.commentary: Sarfaraz Ahmed c †Ronchi b McClenaghan 18 (13b 2x4 0x6 21m) SR: 138.46

dismissalComment.html: taken by Ronchi! Just about! Sarfraz is gone and it's a Mitch that turns a match again. Cross-seamed short ball that followed Sarfraz as he moved outside leg to make room for himself. Goes for a pull on instinct and top-edges it straight up. The rest was taken care of by an alert Ronchi

commentPreTextItems.html: Vettori has a word of confidence for Henry

commentTextItems.html: that's it, just a single to long-on and New Zealand have made it 2-2! What a game it has been! And it ends with the bowler nailing a full ball on middle

commentPostTextItems.html: "I can smell the 5th ODI tied" Wouldn't that be a lovely finish! To find out if Raj Thapa's prediction come true, do join us on Friday same time. But until then, this is Alagappan Muthu saying sayonara

Kane Williamson is the Man of the Match "It was just about executing the plans we had, and just trying to build partnerships. Its such a big ground that you can score freely. They made it quite difficult and it was great to come back with the ball in the second part of the Pakistan innings. Whenever you play in different parts of the world you adapt your game and maybe we've been here so long, I'm getting used to playing like [a subcontinent batsman]. Its important, we look at the final game as a one-off, recover quickly and get back out there. Pakistan kept coming, they showed consistently how good they are. To have 300 on the board on a wicket that was tiring, they pushed us and it was nice to pick up some timely wickets at the end and close it out"

We tried to do our best so that we could win and try and lessen the grief of the families affected by Peshawar as much as possible Shahid Afridi says I was very happy to see Younis Khan's batting. The fielding and the bowling aspects are still of concern to us but the batting has always been strong and that is a positive for us

11.00 pm There couldn't have been too many people who would have predicted a finish as close as this. Adam Milne and Matt Henry were near unplayable at the start of the innings but Younis Khan persisted to make a determined century. He didn't care about his strike-rate, he knew his presence in the middle mattered more and Pakistan had the firepower lower down to capitalise. They almost did with Shahid Afridi playing a blinder and Sarfraz Ahmed showing great pluck. But Kane Williamson, after scoring a century himself to set up the 300-run target, attacked with his trump cards to hike the run-rate up back up past 9 and 10 in the last few overs and his strike bowlers provided him with some wickets as well
David: "Fantastic finish. Impressive closing by NZ's young bowlers. Vettori's still adds a lot too!"
haris: "i'm not sad for pak team defeat i'm happy they played this match under this circumstances nd fight their way to win it though they lose in the end but they don't lose hope #we_are_united"
DanielAlexander: "Series is all square across formats, what a tie breaker the 5th ODI be "

commentPreTextItems.html: 9 off 2. Can Anwar clear the ropes here?

commentTextItems.html: beaten! Brilliant effort from Henry! It was back of a length right on top of off stump, the batsman slogs wildly and can't connect

commentPreTextItems.html: Williamson, Vettori and Henry adjust the field just the way they want. Fine leg is up

commentTextItems.html: length ball on middle, heaved to long-on for a couple
full and on the pads, have to settle for one leg bye as Ronchi runs after it

commentPreTextItems.html: Williamson and Henry in conversation about the field. Long-on in place, third man comes up

commentTextItems.html: low full toss, cracked to the midwicket boundary. Guptill was guarding that region and despite a big dive, it races away

commentPreTextItems.html: So that's 16 off the final over. Who will bowl it? Matt Henry has the ball in hand

commentTextItems.html: short ball, it's the slower one as well. Tanvir wasn't ready for that and he's missed it. Lovely height on the ball, came up to his neck
yorker a shade outside off, clipped to deep midwicket

headshotImage.caption: Anwar Ali player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Anwar Ali player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentPreTextItems.html: sjrn: "A wicket for Vettori on his first and the last ball both. Doesn't happen that often'Does it?"

commentTextItems.html: heaved to deep midwicket, but there is protection there. Offered length, but wasn't capitalised on
nails a yorker on leg stump, but Anwar is able to grab a single towards midwicket. Those deep fielders better be alert

commentPreTextItems.html: Anderson has not come back onto the field since he left a little while earlier

commentTextItems.html: a timely boundary for Pakistan as a shortish delivery has leapt off the top edge to the third man boundary.
full on middle, Tanvir played a loft over long-on too early and toe-ends it along the ground
around the wicket angle cramps Tanvir, who goes for a huge slog to a fuller ball outside off. Misses
148kph, short ball sails over middle stump as he beats Anwar's wild swing. What a spell, 10-2-39-1

headshotImage.longCaption: Anwar Ali player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentPreTextItems.html: Long-on goes back. Deep cover comes up

commentTextItems.html: shortish on middle, Tanvir looks to pull and gets an inside edge onto his body. Loud calls of "yeah" as Pakistan take a single. Bowler raced up to try and effect a run-out but was unable to get the ball
a touch shorter on middle and off, Anwar looks to slap it away again and hits it rather high on the bat. Takes a single as the ball falls short of mid-off

commentPreTextItems.html: KSRV: "and NZ in need of a Maxwell"

commentTextItems.html: slapped to the long-off boundary! How is that for a counterpunch. Cleared that front leg and got enough bat to beat mid-off and race off
back of a length and outside off, Anwar backs away to slash and misses. 150 kph, in his final over.

commentPreTextItems.html: Bayezid: "Pakistan is in a desperate need of a James Faulkner now.... !!!" Milne to bowl out

commentTextItems.html: beats Tanvir for pace as he goes for a pull, ball leaps off the splice of the bat and falls well short of the long leg fielder rushing in
there's the short ball and it skips off the top edge to the third man boundary despite a diving effort from the fielder there. This game is nowhere near over!

dismissalText.commentary: Ahmed Shehzad b Henry 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 2m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: what a delivery! Off stump cartwheels as Henry opens Shehzad up! Speared the ball in at a very full length and it curls away late. Shehzad can't quite be blamed for being stuck on the crease against a ball like that. Pushes with his hands and next second, he hears timber!

dismissalText.commentary: Nasir Jamshed lbw b Anderson 30 (46b 2x4 1x6 53m) SR: 65.21

dismissalComment.html: his footwork has been suspect all through the innings. He was relying solely on his balance and timing so far but this time he's misread an offcutter and has found himself plumb in front. Anderson knew straight away, had a giant grin all through the appeal as the ball gripped in the pitch and veered in at Jamshed to beat the inside edge and hit the back pad in front of all three stumps

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Hafeez c †Ronchi b Vettori 3 (11b 0x4 0x6 12m) SR: 27.27

dismissalComment.html: takes him out first ball! Hafeez keeps back to a good length ball and plays inside the line. He was looking for a push into the off side with an angled face and ends up nicking to the keeper. Good work form Ronchi. That will be drinks as well

dismissalText.commentary: Haris Sohail c Latham b Vettori 13 (25b 2x4 0x6 22m) SR: 52

dismissalComment.html: goes down the track and lifts it down long-on's throat! The pressure tells on Sohail as he strikes the ball off the inside edge and gets too much height. Latham had run in a bit too enthusiastically and has to backtrack to get under the ball

dismissalText.commentary: Umar Akmal run out (McClenaghan) 29 (37b 1x4 0x6 65m) SR: 78.37

dismissalComment.html: that is so unfortunate! Younis has caned a straight drive and Mitch Mc manages to get enough of a deflection back onto the stumps, one of which cartwheels on impact, with Akmal backing up! Among the worst dismissals in cricket

dismissalText.commentary: Shahid Afridi c †Ronchi b Milne 49 (25b 5x4 2x6 36m) SR: 196

dismissalComment.html: Milne has done the trick! The old back-away slash through point ends up as an outside edge to the keeper. What a rollicking innings it has been.

dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan b Vettori 103 (117b 4x4 2x6 199m) SR: 88.03

dismissalComment.html: flat, full and straight. Vettori has toppled Younis and has coolly gone back to the umpire to collect his cap. Wild slog from Younis and he realised his mistake the moment he swung past the ball

dismissalText.commentary: Sarfaraz Ahmed c †Ronchi b McClenaghan 18 (13b 2x4 0x6 21m) SR: 138.46

dismissalComment.html: taken by Ronchi! Just about! Sarfraz is gone and it's a Mitch that turns a match again. Cross-seamed short ball that followed Sarfraz as he moved outside leg to make room for himself. Goes for a pull on instinct and top-edges it straight up. The rest was taken care of by an alert Ronchi
